node.text:
I’ll never get tired of picking barrels. Four fresh ones ready for club members. Two barrels of Elijah Craig (pushing 10 years in age) and a delicious duo of 6-year cask strength (IN) bourbon from Heaven’s Door 💯🥃

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by The Bourbon Enthusiast on August 03, 2021 tagging @heavenhilldistillery. May be an image of bottle.

node.text:
Heaven Hill Distillery announced today the release of the fall 2021 edition of Old Fitzgerald Bottled-in-Bond Kentucky Straight Bourbon Whiskey at 11 years old. “Comprised of barrels produced in spring of 2010, and bottled in spring of 2021, the eighth national release ushers in the latest hallmark series to the bottled-in-bond legacy.

Bottled in an ornate decanter, the fall edition denotes a black label, consistent across all fall releases. As was the case for the past editions, this edition’s tax strip, which has always been a signature of transparency on bottled-in-bond products, will disclose when the liquid was produced and bottled. The Old Fitzgerald Bottled-in-Bond fall edition will be available in the 750ml size on an allocated basis. It meets the strict requirements of a bottled-in-bond: the product of a single distillery from a single distilling season, aged a minimum of four years, and bottled at 100 proof or 50% alcohol by volume. The edition is available at a suggested retail price of 110.”

- 📸 @heavenhilldistillery 

———————————————————————————

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Bourbon Enthusiast in New Riff Distilling with @newriff. May be an image of drink and indoor.

node.text:
This is not your typical rye. With a mashbill of 100% malted rye, it has a sweeter profile than anticipated with terrific notes of chocolate, butterscotch and subtle hints of mint. A nice sipper for sure 👍🥃

———————————————————————————

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by The Bourbon Enthusiast on July 21, 2021 tagging @oldforester. May be an image of bottle and indoor.

node.text:
The 2021 Birthday Bourbon boasts a velvety texture, nice complexity, and interesting notes that differ from recent years. My tasting notes:
On the nose there’s dusty oak, gingerbread, berry cobbler, cinnamon glaze and a hint of black pepper. 
The taste starts with a blast of berry fruits, floral and sharp pine spice, cinnamon, and light caramel. 
The finish is cooked pears, caramelized wood sugars, oak spice, and raisins. 

Releasing in September, this edition is fruity with sharp pine and oak spice elements. The 2021 batch is comprised of just 119 barrels, aged 12 years and bottled at 104 proof. 

———————————————————————————
